 Baldwin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bullen","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from the French Channel port of Boulogne, recorded in Latin sources both as <i>Gessoriacum</i> and as <i>Bononia</i>. The latter name is clearly the source of the modern placename. It is ostensibly a derivative of Latin <i>bonus</i> ‘good’ (compare   Bolognese  ), but may in fact come from a Gaulish element <i>bona</i> ‘foundation’. Boulogne has long been a major trading port between England and France."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice Boleyn was born about 1456, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Robert de Clere. She died in 1538, at the age of 83."},"et":{"Abt 1456–1538":"umbes 1456–1538","1453–1529":"1453–1529","1475–1517":"1475–1517","1456–1538":"1456–1538","10 August 1529":"10. august 1529","1456":"1456","1475":"1475","1453":"1453","Abt 1456":"umbes 1456","abt. 1475":"umbes 1475","1529":"1529","1517":"1517","1538":"1538","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ormesby, Norfolk, England":"Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Isleham, Camb